courses.learning_outcomes:
1. Students are equipped to have the knowledge and critical ability to make a theological reflection of Christian belief and practice;
2. Students are trained to have the intellectual ability and consciousness to correlate theology to other disciplines, such as, science, politics and philosophy;
3. Students are educated to have the knowledge and imagination to construct their own theologies in the context of their everyday life.

1. The students will know and understand

a. the general overview of the contents in the Hebrew Bible;
b. the direct relationship of the composition of the books to her contexts;
c. a general grasp of the scholarship pertaining to the study of the Hebrew Bible;
d. the meaning of the Hebrew Bible as Christian Canon/Scripture.

2. The students can describe, explain and discuss

a. the main issues related to the critical study of the books in the Hebrew Bible;
b. the main issues of critical scholarship concerning the composition and redaction of the books, as well as the origin and identity of Israel;
c. the proposed historical contexts of the Hebrew Bible;
d. the relationships or/and tensions between the traditions underlying the theological motivations and the contemporary situation/s of the text.

3. The students will appreciate

a. the making/compilation of the Hebrew Bible;
b. the necessity for language acquisition in the study of the Hebrew Bible;
c. the diverse research faculties in the study of the Hebrew Bible.

After completing this course, students should be able to:

1. Describe and compare the various theories on the formation of the Pentateuch;
2. Deepen their awareness of how ancient social, cultural, and political contexts may have contributed to the literary production of the Pentateuch;
3. Demonstrate a familiarity of the current approaches to the reading of the Pentateuch;
4. Develop a contextual awareness in their own reading of the Pentateuchal texts.

After completing this course, students should be able to:

1. Describe the compositional background, major literary features, genres, and motifs of the prophetic literature;
2. Deepen their awareness of how social, cultural, and political contexts of ancient Southwest Asia may have shaped the literary production of the prophetic literature;
3. Demonstrate a familiarity of the critical issues and approaches in the scholarship of the Latter Prophets;
4. Develop a contextual awareness in their own reading of the prophetic literature and a critical attitude toward the implications of its ideological content to the contemporary world.

Knowledge Outcome:

- Approach Johannine texts and thoughts in different contexts;

Skills Outcome:

- Access any topic of Johannine studies with the aid of the Forschungsgeschichte;

Attitude Outcome:

- Appraise and critically evaluate the Johannine contributions in shaping different Christian cultures.

On the successful completion of this unit, students should be able to:
1. define exegesis and explain its role in understanding biblical text;
2. outline a step by step procedure for the practice of exegesis;
3. do a word study on a significant key-word in a selected Scripture passages; and
4. demonstrate skill in exegesis for a more effective preaching and teaching ministry.

