courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course, participants should be able to:

1. critically review films from Christian theological perspectives;
2. demonstrate critical understanding of how Christian communities can engage with cinematic media in manners that are theologically informed and socioculturally sensitive;
3. engage fairly competently with important published texts in the field;
4. endeavour with a solid foundation toward further academic work in the interdisciplinary study of film and theology / religion.

 Knowledge: Students acquire the following and/or critically reflect on them--
1. The history and traditions of congregational studies as a theological sub-discipline;
2. Different models, methodologies and methods of congregational studies;
3. Social scientific understandings of the local (Hong Kong) church;
4. Deep understanding of at least one phenomenon (such as church growth, charismatic movement, liturgical reform movement, social concern and involvement, ethical stance such as in the issue of homosexuality, etc.) of the local church;
5. Read at least one classic text in the field of Christian counseling.
 Attitude: students be able to fully appreciate
1. The plurality of church traditions and structures;
2. The interrelationship between a congregational church and its surrounding context;
3. The theological significance of congregational studies;
4. The needs to draw insights from social scientific understandings of human organization to understand a congregational church.
 Skill: students be able to analyze any typical churches social scientifically and theologically.

Knowledge: Students acquire the following and/or critically reflect on them--
1. Reconceiving theology as a practical science;
2. History, traditions and schools of the practical theology movement going on since the 1970s;
3. Methods and Methodologies of doing practical theology;
4. Read at least one classic text in the field of practical theology.
Attitude: students be able to fully appreciate that theological study is practically-oriented;
Skill: students be able to
1. critically do theory-practice integration via theological reflection;
2. critically transfer the knowledge learnt to at least two aspects of Christian practice.

Students be able to:
1. Account for the continuities and discontinuities of intimacy and family relationships in human history;
2. Gain adequate understandings of the biblical and theological traditions in relation to sex, marriage, and family;
3. Interpret human experiences of love, intimacy and family from a theological, historical, feminist, and critical perspective;
4. Critically and theologically evaluate the dominant familial ideologies of their societies;
5. Critically and theologically engage in the discussions of gender related issues, such as the LGBTTTQQIAA movements, feminist movements, etc.;
6. Apply knowledge learnt to critically evaluate public policies and public discourses in relation to sex, marriage, and family;
7. Value and enjoy the divine gifts of sex, celibacy, marriage and family relationship in a profound and biblical sense.

After this course, students should be able to

• recognize and describe the historical context of the composition and readership of the biblical books emerged in the Second Temple Period;
• appreciate the significance and relevance of studying the biblical books emerged in the Second Temple Period;
• analyze the passages from the biblical books emerged in the Second Temple Period using various perspectives;
• theorize the ideology and theology in/of the biblical books emerged in the Second Temple Period;
• reflect and design on the various use of the biblical books emerged in the Second Temple Period in different contexts.

1. Students will have a good grasp of the foundational theories of Religious Education;
2. Students will be able to discern good theories and practices in the field of Religious Education;
3. Students will be confident to create, adapt and develop curricula and courses that would be appropriate for the contexts where they will be serving;
4. Students will be able to further develop and improve their knowledge and skills in Religious Education.

1. Knowledge Outcomes:
- In-depth understanding of the chosen topic in Christian Studies;
- Research on and organization of primary and secondary materials;

2. Skills Outcomes:
- Developing a sound research topic;
- Conducting an independent research study;

3. Attitude Outcomes:
