courses.learning_outcomes:
After completing this course, students should be able to:
Expected Knowledge Outcomes
1. Know the development of the Bible education from a historical perspective;
2. Familiarize oneself with the general educational environment and policies in Hong Kong (and/or China);
3. Compare the Bible education in Hong Kong/China with other parts of the world;
Expected Attitude Outcome
4. Reform and revitalize the Bible education in the Church and the education sector;
Expected Skills Outcome
5. Organize effective Bible ministries in one's church or school setting.

courses.course_syllabus:
Week 1) the mission and the content of Bible education;
Week 2) Bible education in history;
Week 3-4) Bible ministries in Church [I & II]: "Sunday" school, Bible study group & so forth;
Week 5-6) Bible ministries by parachurch organization [I & II];
Week 7) Religious studies (Bible education) in kindergarten;
Week 8-9) Religious studies (Bible education) in primary school [I & II];
Week 10-11) Religious studies (Bible education) in secondary school [I & II];
Week 12-13) Skill training concerning Bible education [I & II].

courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completing the course, students should be able to:

1. understand at the foundational theories of Religious Education;
2. deepen their knowledge and understanding of these theories from the perspective of the Christian religion;
3. assess the courses/programs of Christian Education currently used in denominations and local churches;
4. critically apply the learnt theories by developing a model of Christian Education with a new approach entitled “Praxis in Dimensions”

After completion the course, students should be able to:
1. understand both the main thoughts of modernism and postmodernism;
2. understand how postmodern culture has given challenges to Christian belief and practice;
3. understand the diverse responses to postmodern culture that have been made by various theologians and Christian educators;
4. Critically develop some principles for carrying out Christian Education in Hong Kong with the emergence development of postmodern culture.

Knowledge: Students acquire the following and/or critically reflect on them--
1. The contextuality and situatedness of theological knowledge;
2. The history of contextual theology;
3. Deep understanding of at least four types of contextual theology;
4. Methods and Methodologies of doing practical theology;
5. Read at least one classic text in the field of contextual theology.
Attitude: students be able to fully appreciate that
1. The value of a living faith lies in its openness and contextual relevance;
2. Theologically sound ideas are often praxis-oriented.
Skill: students be able to theologically analyze and interpret social/cultural/political issues going on in their own context.

Knowledge: Students acquire the following and/or critically reflect on them--
1. The history and pre-history of Asian theology since the 1900s;
2. Deep understanding of Asian theologies from at least four regions;
3. Methods and Methodologies of doing Asian theology;
4. Read at least one classic text in the field of Asian theology.
Attitude: students be able to fully appreciate that
1. The notion of normative Christianity is a myth to be deconstructed;
2. Theologically sound ideas are often praxis-oriented;
3. A living faith is one that is open to inter-religious dialogue.
Skill: students be able to theologically analyze and interpret social/cultural/political issues going on in their own context with Asian perspectives.

Upon completing the course, students should be able to:
1. familiarize the discussion between Confucian religious humanism and its counterpart in Christianity. Particular attention will be focused on the dialogue between Confucian understanding of Heaven and Christian personal deity. Capability and sensitivity of human conscience and the work of the Holy Spirit will also be discussed;
2. familiarize the Daoist way of naturalism and freedom. The Way (Dao) as ground of beings in Daoist philosophy of life will be compared with Christian understanding of God’s transcendent and immanent presence in the cosmos and human living;
3. understand self-transcendent experiences in Chinese Buddhism, particularly with Zen (Chan) Buddhism, the Lotus School (Tian-tai Sect) and the Flower Garland School (Hua-yen Sect). Ways to enlightenment in Chinese Buddhist practices will be compared with Christian spiritual discernment directed by the Holy Spirit.

After completion the course, students should be able to:
1. understand traditional Chinese culture from economic, socio-political and cultural analyses;
2. apprehend how to read Chinese culture from Christian theology of culture, theological analysis and critique of economic (socialist and capitalist) systems, also political agendas like democracy and authoritarianism;
3. entertain Christian moral reflection on Chinese ways of life and socio-psychological characters like acquiring face, social relation networking, and gratitude-return tactic agreement;
4. acquire deeper understanding of cultural embedment in Chinese church and ways to enhance constructive interplay.

By the end of the course, participants should be able to:

1. demonstrate critical understanding of the role of the media in the contemporary society, as well as the relationships between popular media culture and the Christian Church;
2. critically evaluate particular media works in their various forms from Christian theological perspectives;
3. demonstrate familiarity with important texts in the field as well as available theological resources;
4. relate discussions in the course to their personal and communal experience of media consumption and involvement;
5. use the foundation built in this course for further academic work in areas related to media, popular culture, and theology.

Knowledge: Students acquire the following and/or critically reflect on them--
1. The history and traditions of pastoral care;
2. The key functions of pastoral care;
3. How pastoral care is different from other Christian ministries;
4. The contextuality of pastoral care;
5. Read at least one classic text in the field of pastoral care.
Attitude: students be able to fully appreciate
1. The need to integrate pastoral experience with theological understanding;
2. The need to critically draw insights from social scientific understandings of human being and human society.
Skill: students be able to
1. Apply key concepts of pastoral care to specific contexts and populations, i.e. hospital, school, congregational church;
2. Develop personal and inter-personal leadership skills appropriate to particular areas of contemporary Christian life and ministry, such as worship, preaching, teaching, social ministry, etc.

Upon completing the course, students should be able to:
1. familiarize major trends and representative figures in the two thousand years of Christian spiritual traditions;
2. develop a critical understanding of the various traditions in their cultural contexts and possible contemporary applicability;
3. identify the different between spiritual experiences and practices of spiritual self-transcendence and personal encounter with the deity as a personal other.

Knowledge: Students acquire the following and/or critically reflect on them--
1. The history and traditions of Christian counseling
2. The similarities and differences between Christian counseling and General Counseling;
3. The similarities and differences between Christian counseling and pastoral care;
4. Different approaches to Christian counseling;
5. Counseling ministries in some specific settings, such as bereavement, depression, crisis situations, etc.
6. Read at least one classic text in the field of Christian counseling.
Attitude: students be able to fully appreciate
1. The Christianness of Christian counseling;
2. The need to integrate Christian counseling with theological understanding;
3. The need to critically draw insights from social scientific understandings of human being and human society.
Skill: students be able to
1. Do basic counselling guidance work in Christian settings under professional supervision.

1. Student’s sensitivity to new challenges and common youth problems in Hong Kong is raised;
2. Students are able to acquire an overall understanding of the theories and practice of youth counseling;
3. Students are able to critically analyze field-related research and its applications to practice of youth counseling ministry;
4. Students are able to conduct clinical assessment, under professional supervision, that is grounded in relevant social scientific theories and pastoral theologies;
5. Students are able to use theories and current treatment models to design plans for helping youths in troubles;
6. Students are willing to demonstrate commitment to the ethical standards in relation to working with youth;
7. Students are able to reflect on their own values, personal experiences and stance on different youth issues.
8. Students are able to demonstrate basic competence in working with clients from diverse backgrounds in collaboration with church workers.

1. Student’s sensitivity to new challenges and common family problems in Hong Kong is raised;
2. Students are able to develop a systemic perspective and clinical map about different problems regarding family dynamic.
3. Students are able to critically analyze field-related research and its applications to practice of family counseling ministry;
4. Students are able to conduct clinical assessment, under professional supervision, that is grounded in relevant social scientific theories and pastoral theologies;
5. Students are able to use theories and current treatment models to design plans for helping families in troubles;
6. Students are willing to demonstrate commitment to the ethical standards in relation to working with family;
7. Students are able to reflect on their own values, personal experiences and stance on different family issues.
8. Students are able to demonstrate basic competence in working with clients from diverse backgrounds in collaboration with church workers.

